<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Amendments of Indian Constitution</title>
    <style>
        /* Reset Styles */
        * {
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            box-sizing: border-box;
        }

        /* Global Styles */
        body {
            font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
            background-color: #f9fafb;
            color: #1a202c;
            line-height: 1.6;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            padding: 20px;
        }

        /* Main Container */
        .container {
            max-width: 800px;
            width: 100%;
            background: white;
            border-radius: 10px;
            box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
            overflow: hidden;
        }

        /* Header */
        header {
            background: #1a202c; /* Dark Gray */
            color: #ffffff;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 2rem;
        }

        header h1 {
            font-size: 2.5rem;
        }

        header p {
            margin-top: 0.5rem;
            font-size: 1.2rem;
        }

        /* Section Styles */
        section {
            padding: 2rem;
            border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
        }

        section h2 {
            color: #1a202c;
            font-size: 1.8rem;
            margin-bottom: 1rem;
            border-bottom: 3px solid #2c5282;
            display: inline-block;
            padding-bottom: 0.5rem;
        }

        section p {
            margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
            font-size: 1rem;
        }

        ul {
            list-style: none;
            padding-left: 0;
        }

        ul li {
            background: #edf2f7;
            margin-bottom: 0.8rem;
            padding: 1rem;
            border-radius: 5px;
            font-size: 1rem;
        }

        ul li h3 {
            margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
            color: #2c5282;
            font-size: 1.2rem;
        }

        ul li p {
            margin: 0;
            color: #4a5568;
        }

        /* Footer */
        footer {
            background: #1a202c;
            color: white;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 1rem;
            font-size: 0.9rem;
        }

        /* Responsive Styles */
        @media (max-width: 768px) {
            header h1 {
                font-size: 2rem;
            }

            section h2 {
                font-size: 1.5rem;
            }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <header>
            <h1>Amendments of Indian Constitution</h1>
            <p>A dynamic document adapting to the changing needs of the nation.</p>
        </header>

        <section>
            <h2>Overview of Amendments</h2>
            <p>Since its adoption in 1950, the Constitution of India has been amended over <strong>100 times</strong>. These amendments ensure its relevance while maintaining the core principles of democracy, equality, and justice.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Types of Amendments</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <h3>Simple Majority Amendments</h3>
                    <p>Amendments that affect less critical areas, like state boundaries, require a simple majority in Parliament.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h3>Special Majority Amendments</h3>
                    <p>Changes to critical provisions need a special majority in both Houses of Parliament.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h3>Special Majority and State Ratification</h3>
                    <p>Amendments affecting federal structure require ratification by at least half of the states.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Key Amendments</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <h3>First Amendment (1951)</h3>
                    <p>Placed reasonable restrictions on the right to free speech and facilitated land reforms.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h3>Seventh Amendment (1956)</h3>
                    <p>Reorganized states on linguistic lines.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h3>Forty-Second Amendment (1976)</h3>
                    <p>Strengthened central government powers and introduced terms like "socialist" and "secular" to the Preamble.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h3>One Hundred and First Amendment (2016)</h3>
                    <p>Introduced Goods and Services Tax (GST) to create a unified tax system.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Importance of Amendments</h2>
            <p>Amendments provide a balance between rigidity and flexibility, enabling the Constitution to adapt to evolving political, social, and economic needs while upholding its fundamental principles.</p>
        </section>

        <footer>
            &copy; 2024 Educational Resource on Indian Constitution
        </footer>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
